{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493079"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:55:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:55:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1218"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1218","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1218"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.01,0.04,0.76,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1218"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"29266"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1218","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1218"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1218"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"15425"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1950"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7335"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7387"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42251"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"29266","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/29266"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner with a five week history of rash on her lower limbs.\u0026nbsp; She has a medical history of hypertension, for which she takes ramipril. She has had no recent change in medication. On examination, her vital signs are all within the normal range and she is afebrile. Exposure of the skin demonstrate multiple eruptions as shown (Image 1, 2). Nikolvsky\u2019s sign is negative. Examination of the oral mucosa and conjunctiva are normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pemphigus vulgaris","Lichen planus","Erythema multiforme","Bullous pemphigoid","Dermatitis herpetiformis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is an example of\u003Cstrong\u003E bullous pempihgoid. \u003C/strong\u003EWhilst seen infrequently, bullous pemphigoid is the most common among the immunobullous disorders. It usually presents in older individuals and in addition to the rash, there is severe itchiness and the bullae are tense and large, rupturing to form crusted lesions. It frequently affects areas around skin folds.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPemphigus vulgaris \u003C/strong\u003Epresents with painful blisters and erosion on skin and mucous membrane. These are thin flaccid blisters that rupture easily causing painful itchy erosions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELichen planus \u003C/strong\u003Epresents as a pruritic, purple, polygonal rash with papule or plaques. These are firm and flat, crossed by fine white Wickham striae. \u003Cstrong\u003EErythema multiforme\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by target lesions, most common in young adults, often precipitated by herpes simplex virus infection, as well as other triggers such as other infection, medication and vaccinations. It is mostly self-limiting. \u003Cstrong\u003EDermatitis herpetiformis\u003C/strong\u003E is distinguished by intensely pruritic symmetrical blisters usually affecting extensor surfaces of limbs, linked to coeliac disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Bullous pemphigoid presents with tense blisters, while pemphigus vulgaris has flaccid blisters."],"references":["Oakley A. Bullous pemphigoid [Internet]. DermNet. 2016 [cited 2022Oct21]. Available from: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/bullous-pemphigoid"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"15425"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1218"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17838"},{"type":"media","id":"17839"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17838","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17838"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2de0ac6b-2257-4412-89a5-e5cab3973ed4.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2de0ac6b-2257-4412-89a5-e5cab3973ed4.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":352}},{"type":"media","id":"17839","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17839"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/aee4b876-b681-4888-abe7-3cba10973ba1.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/aee4b876-b681-4888-abe7-3cba10973ba1.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":548,"height":389}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"15425","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/15425"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2022-10-23T12:11:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2022-10-23T12:11:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1218"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"29266"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relation